<section xml:id="sec-vector-algebra" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Vector algebra</title>

<p>There are two main operations which can be performed on vectors. The first is addition. 
We add vectors by adding their components.</p>


<definition xml:id="def-sum-vec">
<statement>
<p>Given two vectors <m>\vect{a} = [a_1, a_2]</m> and <m>\vect{b} = [b_1, b_2]</m>, the sum of <m>\vect{a}</m> and <m>\vect{b}</m> is
<me>
\vect{a} + \vect{b} = [a_1 + b_1, a_2 + a_2]
</me>.</p>
</statement>
</definition>


<example xml:id="ex-adding-vectors">
<statement>
<p>If <m>\vect{a} = [3, 6]</m> and <m>\vect{b} = [1, -1]</m>, then <m>\vect{a} + \vect{b} = [3 +1, 6+ (-1)] = [4, 5]</m>.</p>
</statement>
</example>
<p>Geometrically, vectors are added `tip to tail'. Here's what this means. To calculate <m>\vect{a} + \vect{b}</m> 
  geometrically, there are two steps.
<ol>
<li>
<p>Position <m>\vect{b}</m> so that its tail touches the tip of <m>\vect{a}</m>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>To find <m>\vect{a} + \vect{b}</m>, draw the arrow that completes the triangle with other two sides <m>\vect{a}</m> and <m>\vect{b}</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
In other words, <m>\vect{a} + \vect{b}</m> is then vector with its tail at the tail 
of <m>\vect{a}</m>, and with tip at the tip of <m>\vect{b}</m>, as shown in <xref ref="fig-ttt"/>.</p>

