<p>Addition of vectors is <term>commutative</term>, which means that for any 
vectors <m>\vect{a}, \vect{b} \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>,
<me>
\vect{a} + \vect{b} = \vect{b} + \vect{a}
</me>.
</p>
<p>This is shown geometrically by the <term>parallelogram rule</term> in <xref ref="fig-parallrule"/>.</p>
<p>We can also prove this algebraically. (You might want to assume that anything called addition or 
using the symbol <m>+</m> is commutative, because we know that <m>a + b = b+a</m> 
when <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are real or complex numbers. But since vector addition is a new operation, 
we need to prove it.) The proof is that
<md>
<mrow>
\vect{a} + \vect{b} \amp  = [a_1, a_2] + [b_1, b_2] = [a_1 + b_1, a_2 + b_2] \\
\amp  =[b_1 + a_1, b_2 + a_2] = [b_1, b_2] + [a_1, a_2]  \\
\amp  =\vect{b} + \vect{a}
</mrow>
</md>.</p>



