<p>Vector addition is also <term>associative</term>, which means that for all vectors <m>\vect{a}, \vect{b}, \vect{c} \in \R^2</m>,
<me>
(\vect{a} + \vect{b}) + \vect{c} = \vect{a} + (\vect{b} + \vect{c})
</me>.
</p>

<p>The second main vector operation is scaling. We may call real numbers <term>scalars</term>, since 
they are used to scale vectors.</p>


<definition xml:id="def-scaling">
<statement>
<p>Let <m>c \in \R</m> be a scalar and <m>\vect{a} = [a_1, a_2] \in \R^2</m> a vector. The 
<term>scalar multiple</term> <m>c\vect{a}</m> is the vector
<me>
c\vect{a} = [ca_1, ca_2]
</me>.</p>
</statement>
</definition>


<p>Geometrically, <m>c</m> scales <m>\vect{a}</m> by a factor of <m>|c|</m>, and flips
 <m>\vect{a}</m> if <m>c \lt  0</m>.</p>

<p>
<term>Special cases:</term> <m>1\vect{a} = \vect{a}</m>, and <m>0\vect{a} = \vect{0}</m>. We 
define the <term>negative</term> of <m>\vect{a}</m> by <m>-\vect{a} = (-1)\vect{a}</m>. 
Then <m>-\vect{a}</m> has the same length but the opposite direction of <m>\vect{a}</m>.</p>

<example xml:id="ex-scale">
<statement>
<p>Let <m>\vect{a} = [2, 1].</m> Find <m>3\vect{a}</m>, <m>0\vect{a}</m> and <m>-\frac{1}{2}\vect{a}</m>.</p>
<p>Algebraically, <m>3\vect{a} = 3[2, 1] = [6, 3]</m>, <m>0\vect{a} = 0</m>, and 
<m>-\frac{1}{2}\vect{a} = [-1, -1/2]</m>. This is shown geometrically in <xref ref="fig-scale-ex"/>.</p>

